<DOC><DOCNO> AP881123-0118 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-23-88 1218EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Britain-Hotel     11-23 0178</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Britain-Hotel,0185</SECOND><HEAD>Famous Hotel Fined For Health, Safety Violations</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Dorchester, one of London's grandest hotels,has been fined about $11,900 for violating health and safetyregulations.   Prosecutor Geoffrey Stevenson told Bow Street Magistrates Courton Tuesday that health officers in March found part of the hotel'smain kitchen infested with cockroaches.   The Sultan of Brunei, one of the world's richest men, paid $55.9million for the 280-bedroom hotel on swank Park Lane in 1985.   The 57-year-old hotel was headquarters for Gen. Dwight D.Eisenhower, the Allied Supreme Commander in World War II.   On behalf of the hotel, lawyer Patrick Hamlin pleaded guilty to17 counts of infringing food and hygiene regulations and one countunder safety regulations charging the kitchen floor was slipperywith grease and very dangerous.   Stevenson said kitchen ceilings, walls, an open gully and cookingequipment were covered in grease.   Since the inspection, the hotel has spent $170,190 improving thekitchen, Hamlin said.   An average single room at the Dorchester costs $219 a night anddinner for one about $54.</TEXT></DOC>